[2] China: vaccine comment
Date: Mon 30 Apr 2018
From: Jean-Pierre Dhenin http://www.ufh.com.cn/


China has a vaccine against enterovirus-71.
Vaccine enterovirus type 71 (inactivated) injection 0.5 ml 1/box

Immunization indicated age: 6 months old- 5-year-old susceptible children
Schedule: 2 doses, 1 month apart
Dose: 0.5 ml intramuscularly
(not in regular immunization schedule; it is on demand by parent's choice)

--
Dr Jean-Pierre Dhenin
Attending Physician, Dept. of Family Medicine, Beijing
United Family Hospital and Clinics (BJU)
United Family Healthcare
http://www.ufh.com.cn/

[ProMED thanks Dr Dhenin for submitting this information on the enterovirus 71 vaccine in use in China.

For further information on the vaccine, see:
- Zhu F, Xu W, Xia J, et al. Efficacy, safety, and immunogenicity of an enterovirus 71 vaccine in China. N Engl J Med. 2014; 370(9): 818-28. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa1304923; available at http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1304923.
- Li R, Liu L, Mo Z, et al. An inactivated enterovirus 71 vaccine in healthy children, N Engl J Med. 2014; 370(9): 829-37. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa1303224; available at http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1303224

Two vero cell-based EV71 inactivated whole virus vaccines with aluminum hydroxide were consistently shown to induce immune responses to EV71 in infants and young children, 6-35 months (Fengcai Zhu et al.) or 6-71 months (Rongcheng Li et al.) of age, following 2 intramuscular doses, for at least 1 year. A neutralizing antibody titer of 1:16 was associated with protection against EV71.

While these vaccines appear effective against the C4 strain of EV 71 (that is, the one that's caused most epidemics in South East Asia), they do not provide cross-protection against other circulating lineages or against coxsackievirus A16 infection, which also triggers the same syndromes. - Mod.LK]
